article.headline: Bowers sparks Mississippi State with 25 points
article.linkText: Red-hot Bowers propels Bulldogs to rout of Auburn
article.story: AUBURN, Ala. (AP) -- With pinpoint shooting and smothering defense, Timmy Bowers and No. 19 Mississippi State showed Auburn how to play in a game with big stakes. Bowers scored a career-high 25 points on 9-of-13 shooting as the Bulldogs took over the SEC Western Division lead with a 63-46 victory over the Tigers on Wednesday night. Forget the all-games-are-created equal spiel. The Bulldogs (17-5, 7-4 Southeastern Conference) wanted to move closer to a division title. "We prepared for it differently, we pointed to it differently,'' Mississippi State coach Rick Stansbury said. "I don't think there's any question our players came in here and took a big step toward getting that done.'' The Bulldogs held the Tigers (17-7, 6-5) to a season low in points and dominated the boards 40-30 to break the teams' deadlock atop the West. "Our kids have not been in that situation,'' Auburn coach Cliff Ellis said. "They've got to learn to be successful. "We've got to change our focus on the game. We've got to play to win instead of not to lose.'' Mario Austin had 14 points and 12 rebounds for Mississippi State, which has won seven of its last eight conference games after starting 0-3. Bowers, who had 17 points in the first half, was 4-of-6 from 3-point range. "We haven't been given much respect in the SEC,'' he said. "We have been winning our games on the road and that's what good basketball teams do. We came in here and played like a first-place team. "We knew we were the better team.'' Auburn, which has lost five of seven since a 4-0 start, has dropped the past four meetings. Marquis Daniels scored 13 of his 17 points in the second half for the Tigers, who went 4-of-15 from the free throw line and shot just 33 percent, including 4-of-21 on 3-pointers. "Our slumps just came at a bad time of the year,'' said center Kyle Davis, who had seven points, 11 rebounds and six blocked shots. "We'll be OK if we just stay focused and can still win this thing.'' Daniels was 7-of-19 from the field while Davis was 1-of-7 from the line, but had eight offensive boards. Marco Killingsworth was the only Auburn player to hit half his shots or more, going 5-of-7 for 11 points. Auburn scored the first 10 points of the second half and cut it to 35-29 on a 3-pointer by Daniels less than four minutes in. The Bulldogs then scored the next seven points, capped by Ontario Harper's 3-pointer, and led by at least nine the rest of the way. "We knew Auburn was going to make a run at us,'' Stansbury said. "They're too good a basketball team. "The biggest thing you've got to do is not panic. Our kids have been through a lot this year and they've got a lot of confidence.'' The game featured two of the league's top defensive teams, but only one was really effective, especially in the first half. The Bulldogs took a 35-19 halftime lead, holding Auburn to one field goal over the final five minutes and 7-of-28 shooting. The also were just 3-of-10 from the free-throw line. Bowers was as hot as Auburn was cold, shooting 7-of-8 and making three 3-pointers. "After I made that first 3-pointer, my confidence was pretty high and I just started knocking down shots,'' he said. Harper stole the ball and found Zimmerman for a wide-open dunk with 39 seconds left as Mississippi State closed the half on a 25-9 run over the final 12 minutes. It matched Auburn's fewest points for a half, equaling the first half against Western Michigan. Ellis wanted his players to be more aggressive. That wasn't a problem for the Bulldogs. "We came out and played aggressively,'' Austin said, "but we won the game with our defense.''
